] for [[Florida's 26th congressional district]], elected in [[United States House of Representatives elections, 2014|2014]]. He is a [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]. Prior to his election to the U.S. House, he served on the [[Miami-Dade County Public School|school board]] for [[Miami-Dade County]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nCurbelo is the son of [[Cuban exile]]s in Florida.<ref>Werner, Erica. [http://hosted.ap.org/dynamic/stories/U/US_NEW_HOUSE_REPUBLICANS?SITE=AP&SECTION=HOME&TEMPLATE=DEFAULT&CTIME=2014-11-08-09-17-42 House GOP boasts diversity and new conservatives] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141111200258/http://hosted.ap.org/dynamic/stories/U/US_NEW_HOUSE_REPUBLICANS?SITE=AP&SECTION=HOME&TEMPLATE=DEFAULT&CTIME=2014-11-08-09-17-42 |date=November 11, 2014 }}, [[Associated Press]], November 8, 2014</ref> He attended [[Belen Jesuit Preparatory School]].<ref name=\"votesmart\"/> He attended the [[University of Miami]], where he earned bachelor's and master's degrees in [[public administration]].<ref name=\"votesmart\"/>\n\n==Career==\n[[File:Carlos Curbelo and Danny Lopez blog the debate (2100723430).jpg|thumb|right|Curbelo in 2007]]\nCurbelo previously served on the [[Miami-Dade County Public Schools]] board from 2010 to 2015.<ref>http://media.cq.com/members/54988?rel=memberLink</ref><ref name=\"MiamiHerldMazzei11052014\">Mazzei, Patricia, Christina Veiga, and Daniel Chang. [http://www.miamiherald.com/news/local/community/miami-dade/article3569095.html In GOP pickup, Miami Rep. Joe Garcia loses to Carlos Curbelo], ''[[Miami Herald]]'', November 5, 2014.</ref> He won the seat vacated by [[Ana Rivas Logan]].<ref>https://www.miamiherald.com/opinion/editorials/article1937046.html</ref> Curbelo represented the 7th district.<ref>https://web.archive.org/web/20120517093037/http://district7.dadeschools.net/</ref><ref>https://web.archive.org/web/20101211152317/http://www2.dadeschools.net:80/schoolboard/bdmembers.asp</ref> He was succeeded by Lubby Navarro on the school board.<ref>http://www.politicalcortadito.com/2015/02/13/lubby-navarro-is-named-to-miami-dade-school-board/</ref> Curbelo is the founder of Capitol Gains, a government and public relations firm.<ref name=\"votesmart\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://dailyentertainmentnews.com/politics/cecilia-curbelo-miami-congressional-candidate-carlos-curbelos-wife/|title=Cecilia Curbelo: Miami congressional candidate Carlos Curbelo's Wife (bio, wiki, photos)|work=DailyEntertainmentNews.com|accessdate=November 5, 2014}}</ref>\n\nHe is also a former state director for former U.S. senator [[George LeMieux]] of Florida.<ref name=\"MiamiHerldMazzei11052014\"/>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n[[File:Florida-representatives-take-oath-miami-federal-courthouse.jpg|thumb|Chief Judge [[Kevin Michael Moore]], swearing in members of Congress: Carlos Curbelo (R), [[Frederica Wilson]] (D), [[Mario D\u00edaz-Balart]] (R), and [[Ileana Ros-Lehtinen]] (R). ''(February 2015)'']]\n\n===Elections===\n;2014\nIn the [[United States House of Representatives elections in Florida, 2014#District 26|2014 election]], Curbelo defeated [[incumbent]] [[Joe Garcia]] of the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]] by 52 to 48 percent.<ref name=\"MiamiHerldMazzei11052014\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.local10.com/news/fight-for-district-26-heats-up-at-polls-in-southwest-miamidade/29527752|title=Carlos Curbelo defeats Joe Garcia in fight for District 26|author=WPLG|work=Local10|accessdate=November 5, 2014}}</ref>\n\n{{Election box begin no change\n|title= 2014 Election for U.S. Representative of Florida's 26th Congressional District<ref>{{cite web|url=https://results.elections.myflorida.com/Index.asp?ElectionDate=11/4/2014&DATAMODE=|title=Florida Department of State - Election Results|first=Sanford|last=Brill|website=results.elections.myflorida.com|accessdate=December 28, 2017}}</ref>\n}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change\n |party = Republican Party (United States)\n |candidate = Carlos Curbelo\n |votes = 83,031\n |percentage = 51.50\n }}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n |party = Democratic Party (United States)\n |candidate = Joe Garcia\n |votes = 78,306\n |percentage = 48.50\n }}\n{{Election box total no change\n  |votes = 161,337\n  |percentage = 100\n  }}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n;2016\nCurbelo ran for [[United States House of Representatives elections in Florida, 2016|re-election in 2016]]. He was unopposed in the Republican primary.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Derby|first1=Kevin|title=Paul Ryan Doubles Down on Support of Carlos Curbelo|url=http://www.sunshinestatenews.com/story/paul-ryan-doubles-down-support-carlos-curbelo|accessdate=February 22, 2016|publisher=Sunshine State New|date=December 30, 2015}}</ref> In the general election, Curbelo defeated former Democratic U.S. representative [[Joe Garcia]]. Curbelo received 53% of the vote.<ref>{{cite news|title=Florida U.S. House 26th District Results: Carlos Curbelo Wins|url=https://www.nytimes.com/elections/results/florida-house-district-26-curbelo-garcia|accessdate=November 17, 2016|publisher=The New York Times|date=November 17, 2016}}</ref>\n\n{{Election box begin no change\n|title= 2016 Election for U.S. Representative of Florida's 26th Congressional District<ref>{{cite web|url=https://results.elections.myflorida.com/Index.asp?ElectionDate=11/8/2016&DATAMODE=|title=Florida Department of State - Election Results|first=Sanford|last=Brill|website=results.elections.myflorida.com|accessdate=December 28, 2017}}</ref>\n}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change\n |party = Republican Party (United States)\n |candidate = Carlos Curbelo\n |votes = 148,547\n |percentage = 53.00\n }}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n |party = Democratic Party (United States)\n |candidate = Joe Garcia\n |votes = 115,493\n |percentage = 41.20\n }}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n | party= Independent politician\n |candidate = Jos\u00e9 Peixoto\n |votes = 16,502\n |percentage = 5.90\n }}\n{{Election box total no change\n  |votes = 280,542\n  |percentage = 100\n  }}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n===Committee assignments===\nIn the 115th Congress, Curbelo sits on the following committee and subcommittees:<ref>{{Citation | url = https://curbelo.house.gov/about/committees.htm | title = Rep. Curbelo Committees and Caucuses | publisher = [[United States House of Representatives]] | accessdate = March 30, 2017}}</ref>\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Ways and Means]]'''\n** [[United States House Ways and Means Subcommittee on Human Resources]]\n** [[United States House Ways and Means Subcommittee on Oversight]]\n\n===Tenure===\nCurbelo has a reputation as a moderate Republican. According to ''[[The McClatchy Company|McClatchy]]'', \"Curbelo has broken ranks with his party to take lonely stands on high-profile topics ranging from abortion and women\u2019s health to climate change, the environment, immigration and government spending.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mcclatchydc.com/news/politics-government/election/article106709612.html|title=Carlos Curbelo isn\u2019t your typical Republican congressman from Miami|date=October 7, 2016|publisher=McClatchy|last1=Rosen|first1=James|accessdate=November 1, 2016}}</ref> Curbelo was ranked the fourth most bipartisan member of the U.S. House of Representatives during first session of the [[115th United States Congress]] by the Bipartisan Index, created by [[Richard Lugar#The Lugar Center|The Lugar Center]] and the [[McCourt School of Public Policy]] to assess [[United States Congress|congressional]] bipartisanship.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thelugarcenter.org/assets/htmldocuments/Senate%20Scores%20115th%20Congress%20First%20Session.pdf|publisher=The Lugar Center|title=The Lugar Center - McCourt School Bipartisan Index|date=April 24, 2018|access-date=July 2, 2018|location=Washington, D.C.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.tampabay.com/florida-politics/buzz/2018/04/26/these-two-florida-lawmakers-rank-among-the-most-bipartisan-members-of-congress/|title=These two Florida lawmakers rank among the most bipartisan members of Congress|publisher=The Tampa Bay Times|location=Tampa Bay, Florida|date=April 26, 2018|accessdate=July 2, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2017, Curbelo made a bid to join the [[Congressional Hispanic Caucus]], which is made up of 30 Democratic members of Congress. After Curbelo made a presentation to the group, caucus membership took a vote and refused to admit him to its membership. Members of the caucus cited Curbelo's vote in favor of repealing Obamacare and his stance on immigration as reasons to deny him membership. Curbelo had not yet signed on as a cosponsor of the [[DREAM Act]], though he said he would vote in favor of any proposal to help undocumented youth who came to the U.S. as children.<ref name=\":4\">[http://www.miamiherald.com/news/politics-government/article184983023.html Miami Herald: \"Hispanic caucus tells Cuban American he can\u2019t join the club \u2014 he\u2019s too Republican\" By Alex Daugherty] November 16, 2017</ref> In January 2018, the Congressional Hispanic Caucus announced that its political arm would support Democrat Debbie Mucarsel-Powell in her 2018 bid for Curbelo's seat.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Daugherty|first1=Alex|title=The Hispanic Caucus spurned Carlos Curbelo. Now they\u2019re backing his opponent|url=http://www.miamiherald.com/news/politics-government/article195126814.html|accessdate=January 24, 2018|publisher=Miami Herald|date=January 17, 2018}}</ref> In an editorial, the ''[[Miami Herald]]'' criticized the caucus' decision to exclude Curbelo from its ranks, writing that \"not letting Curbelo join the caucus remains a short-sighted, spiteful move\" and that \"The caucus should make clear that it's an exclusive club for Democrats, and that Republicans need not apply \u2014 even if they're Hispanic.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Hispanic Caucus shouldn\u2019t have closed the door in Curbelo\u2019s face|url=http://www.miamiherald.com/opinion/editorials/article196291899.html|accessdate=January 24, 2018|publisher=Miami Herald|date=January 23, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAs of September 2018, Curbelo had voted with his party 86.3% of the time so far in the [[115th United States Congress]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://projects.propublica.org/represent/members/C001107-carlos-curbelo|title=Represent|last=|first=|access-date=September 26, 2018|language=en|newspaper=ProPublica}}</ref>\n\nCurbelo is a member of the [[United States Congressional International Conservation Caucus]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Our Members|author=|url=https://royce.house.gov/internationalconservation/members.html|publisher=U.S. House of Representatives International Conservation Caucus |date=|accessdate=August 1, 2018}}</ref> the\n[[Republican Main Street Partnership]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|author=|url=https://republicanmainstreet.org/members/|format=|publisher=Republican Mains Street Partnership|date=|accessdate=October 2, 2017}}</ref> and the [[Climate Solutions Caucus]].<ref>{{cite web|title=90 Current Climate Solutions Caucus Members|author=|url=https://citizensclimatelobby.org/climate-solutions-caucus/|format=|publisher=Citizen\u00b4s Climate Lobby |date=|accessdate=18 October 2018}}</ref> Along with [[Ileana Ros-Lehtinen]], he is one of two Republican members of the [[Congressional LGBT Equality Caucus]] serving in the [[115th United States Congress]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Devaney|first1=Tim|title=LGBT Republican groups campaigning for Curbelo in Fla.|url=http://thehill.com/regulation/304158-gay-republicans-campaigning-for-curbelo|accessdate=January 23, 2018|publisher=The Hill|date=November 3, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Political positions==\n\n===Vote Smart issue positions===\n[[Project Vote Smart|Vote Smart]], a non-profit, non-partisan research organization that collects and distributes information on candidates for public office in the United States, \"researched presidential and congressional candidates' public records to determine candidates' likely responses on certain key issues.\" According to Vote Smart's 2016 analysis, Curbelo generally supports pro-life legislation, opposes an income tax increase, opposes mandatory minimum sentences for non-violent drug offenders, supports lowering taxes as a means of promoting economic growth, opposes requiring states to adopt federal education standards, supports building the [[Keystone Pipeline]], supports government funding for the development of renewable energy, supports the federal regulation of greenhouse gas emissions, supports repealing the [[Affordable Care Act]], opposes requiring immigrants who are unlawfully present to return to their country of origin before they are eligible for citizenship, supports same-sex marriage, supports increased American intervention in [[Iraq]] and [[Syria]] beyond air support, and supports allowing individuals to divert a portion of their [[Social Security (United States)|Social Security]] taxes into personal retirement accounts.<ref>{{cite web|title=Carlos Curbelo's Issue Positions (Political Courage Test)|url=https://votesmart.org/candidate/political-courage-test/137676/carlos-curbelo/#.Wmeh8UtG12R|publisher=[[Vote Smart]]|accessdate=January 23, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Environment===\nIn February 2016, Curbelo and Democratic representative [[Ted Deutch]] created the bipartisan [[Climate Solutions Caucus]] in the House to \u201cexplore policy options that address the impacts, causes, and challenges of our changing climate.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/marcia-g-yerman/rep-carlos-curbelo-republ_b_9240712.html|title=Rep. Carlos Curbelo: Republican Half of the Bipartisan Climate Solutions Caucus|date=February 17, 2016|publisher=Huffington Post|last1=Yerman|first1=Marcia G.|accessdate=February 22, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://dotearth.blogs.nytimes.com/2016/02/06/as-rubio-waffles-two-floridians-in-the-house-seek-bipartisan-climate-progress/|title=As Rubio Waffles, Two Floridians in the House Seek Bipartisan Climate Solutions|date=February 6, 2016|publisher=New York Times|last1=Revkin|first1=Andrew|accessdate=February 22, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Curbelo had the second highest rating of House Republicans on the annual scorecard of the [[League of Conservation Voters]]. The ''[[Miami Herald]]'' wrote that Curbelo has \"attempted to position himself as the national voice for Republicans who are concerned about climate change,\" describing him as \"one of the few GOP voices speaking out against Donald Trump's decision to withdraw from the [[Paris Agreement|Paris Climate Agreement]] and his desire to dismantle the [[Environmental Protection Agency]].\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Daugherty|first1=Alex|title=Carlos Curbelo wants to be a Republican leader on climate change \u2014 if he can keep his seat|url=http://www.miamiherald.com/news/politics-government/article158911839.html|accessdate=January 23, 2018|publisher=Miami Herald|date=June 29, 2017}}</ref> Curbelo described [[climate change]] as a \"local issue\" that is causing flooding in his congressional district. Speaking about his efforts to convince his fellow Republicans about the threats posed by [[climate change]], Curbelo told the ''New York Times'' \"I know we have the truth on our side. So I'm confident that we'll win \u2014 eventually.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Davenport|first1=Coral|last2=Lipton|first2=Eric|title=How G.O.P. Leaders Came to View Climate Change as Fake Science|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/06/03/us/politics/republican-leaders-climate-change.html|accessdate=January 23, 2018|publisher=New York Times|date=June 3, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2017, Curbelo and eleven other House Republicans signed a letter to [[Mitch McConnell]] urging the U.S. Senate \"to pass a tax bill without oil-drilling concessions in the [[Arctic National Wildlife Refuge]].\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Daugherty|first1=Alex|title=Miami Republican opposes allowing Arctic oil drilling in tax bill|url=http://www.miamiherald.com/news/politics-government/article188037329.html|accessdate=January 23, 2018|publisher=Miami Herald|date=December 5, 2017}}</ref><ref>Daughtery, Alex. (December 6, 2017). \"House moderates oppose allowing Arctic oil drilling in tax bill\". [http://www.mcclatchydc.com/news/politics-government/congress/article188094939.html McClatchy DC website] Retrieved December 11, 2017.</ref> Curbelo voted in favor of the final bill, which \"includes a provision, introduced by Sen. [[Lisa Murkowski]] (R-Alaska), that would require Interior Secretary [[Ryan Zinke]] to approve at least two lease sales for drilling \u2014 each covering no less than 400,000 acres \u2014 in the refuge's coastal plain area.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=D'Angelo|first1=Chris|title=6 Republicans Who Said They Oppose Arctic Refuge Drilling Just Voted To Allow It|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/arctic-refuge-drilling-tax-bill_us_5a3960dfe4b0c65287acc76c|accessdate=January 23, 2018|publisher=HuffPost|date=December 19, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2018, Curbelo called for the resignation of [[Administrator of the Environmental Protection Agency]] [[Scott Pruitt]], saying Pruitt's \"corruption scandals are an embarrassment\" and that Pruitt's \"conduct is grossly disrespectful to American taxpayers.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Killough|first1=Ashley|last2=Walsh|first2=Deirdre|last3=Sanchez|first3=Boris|title=2 Florida Republicans call for Trump's EPA chief to resign|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/04/03/politics/curbelo-pruitt/index.html|accessdate=May 18, 2018|publisher=CNN|date=April 3, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2018, Curbelo became the first Republican in nearly a decade to propose legislation on enacting a carbon tax to address the climate change. As part of the proposal, existing taxes on gasoline and diesel fuels would be repealed, and taxes would be introduced on carbon dioxide emissions that starts at $24/ton of CO2e in 2020. According to the Columbia University SIPA Center for Global Energy Policy, Curbelo's legislation would reduce net greenhouse gas emissions by 27\u201332 percent reductions by 2025 and 30\u201340 percent reductions by 2030 (compared to 2005 levels). The legislation was also estimated to increase annual federal government revenues by $57 billion\u2013$72 billion in 2020 and $63 billion\u2013$106 billion in 2030. National macroeconomic outcomes were estimated to decline modestly, with losses between 0.1 and 0.2 percent of GDP in the 2020s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://energypolicy.columbia.edu/research/report/emissions-energy-and-economic-implications-curbelo-carbon-tax-proposal|title=Columbia {{!}} SIPA Center on Global Energy Policy {{!}} Emissions, Energy, and Economic Implications of the Curbelo Carbon Tax Proposal|website=energypolicy.columbia.edu|language=en|access-date=July 22, 2018}}</ref> Other Republicans disavowed the legislation, with the Republican-led House passing a nonbinding measure in July 2018 describing the legislation as \"detrimental\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://thehill.com/homenews/house/397848-house-votes-to-disavow-carbon-tax|title=House votes to disavow carbon tax|last=Rowland|first=Geoffrey|date=July 19, 2018|work=TheHill|access-date=July 22, 2018|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://insideclimatenews.org/news/19072018/anti-carbon-tax-resolution-house-vote-climate-solutions-caucus-curbelo-scalise-koch-influence-congress|title=House Votes to Denounce Carbon Taxes. Where Was the Climate Solutions Caucus?|date=July 19, 2018|work=InsideClimate News|access-date=July 22, 2018|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.miamiherald.com/news/politics-government/article215156110.html|title=Republicans scoff at a carbon tax as Curbelo unveils his own climate-change plan|work=miamiherald|access-date=July 22, 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\n===Healthcare===\nSpeaking about the [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act|Affordable Care Act (\"Obamacare\")]], Curbelo said: \"I clearly do not support the law and think it is bad policy. ... However I prefer to use the word 'replace' or 'substitute' Obamacare because to just say 'repeal' implies that there is no need for health care reform. But yes, if we replace or substitute Obamacare, that means it would no longer exist.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.politifact.com/florida/statements/2014/jul/31/ed-macdougall/carlos-curbelo-opposes-repeal-obamacare-says-attac/|title=Carlos Curbelo 'opposes the repeal of Obamacare,' says attack ad|work=@politifact|access-date=February 26, 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\nOn May 3, 2017, Curbelo [[Twitter|tweeted]] that \"I just reiterated to @HouseGOP leaders that #AHCA in its current form fails to sufficiently protect Americans with pre-existing conditions.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/05/02/politics/republican-health-care-bill/index.html|title=House to vote Thursday on Obamacare repeal bill|last=CNN|first=MJ Lee, Lauren Fox, Tami Luhby and Phil Mattingly|website=CNN|access-date=May 5, 2017}}</ref> On May 4, 2017, he voted to repeal the [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act]] and pass the [[American Health Care Act of 2017|American Health Care Act]] (AHCA).<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/graphics/politics/ahca-house-vote/|title=How the House voted to pass the GOP health-care bill|website=Washington Post|access-date=May 4, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.miaminewtimes.com/news/miami-reps-carlos-curbelo-and-mario-diaz-balart-vote-to-repeal-obamacare-9324792|title=Miami Reps. Carlos Curbelo and Mario Diaz-Balart Voted to Repeal Obamacare|last=Iannelli|first=Jerry|date=May 4, 2017|work=Miami New Times|access-date=May 4, 2017}}</ref> Explaining his vote, Curbelo said the AHCA was \"not perfect, but that it was important for him to be a part of negotiations\" and that the vote \"is just a step in the legislative process for this bill \u2014 not the end of it.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Seitz-Wald|first1=Alex|title=This Republican Is an Endangered Species|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/storyline/democrats-vs-trump/republican-endangered-species-n756151|accessdate=January 23, 2018|publisher=NBC News|date=May 8, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Donald Trump===\nIn March 2016, Curbelo said he would not vote for [[Donald Trump]] in the 2016 presidential election, calling it \"a moral decision\" rather than a political decision.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sunshinestatenews.com/story/carlos-curbelo-wont-vote-donald-trump-open-voting-hillary-clinton|title=Curbelo Won't Vote for Trump, Could Vote for Clinton|date=March 25, 2016|publisher=Sunshine State News|last1=Derby|first1=Kevin|accessdate=March 31, 2016}}</ref> He did not attend the [[2016 Republican National Convention]]. In October 2016, speaking about the upcoming presidential election, he said: \"I'm not supporting any of the two major candidates. I'm as disappointed with this election as most Americans are.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Rosen|first1=James|title=Hates Hillary, despises Trump. What\u2019s a poor congressman to do?|url=http://www.mcclatchydc.com/news/nation-world/national/article105680526.html|accessdate=January 23, 2018|publisher=McClatchy DC Bureau|date=October 3, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2017, while serving on the Ways and Means Committee, he voted against a measure that would have led to a request of the Treasury Department for Trump's tax returns.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2017/02/these-23-republicans-passed-on-a-chance-to-get-trumps-tax-returns/516768/|title=These 23 Republicans Passed on a Chance to Get Trump's Tax Returns|last=Friedersdorf|first=Conor|newspaper=The Atlantic|access-date=February 16, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref> He then voted against a resolution that would have directed the House to request 10 years of Trump's tax returns, which would then have been reviewed by the [[United States House Committee on Ways and Means|House Ways and Means Committee]] in a closed session.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://indy100.com/article/republican-vote-donald-trump-tax-president-united-states-229-185-congress-7603851|title=These are all the Republicans who don\u2019t want you to see Donald Trump\u2019s tax returns|date=February 28, 2017|work=indy100|access-date=March 1, 2017|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n''[[Quartz (publication)|Quartz]]'' included Curbelo on a list of Republicans opposing Trump's 2017 [[Executive Order 13769|executive order]] to impose a temporary ban on entry to the U.S. of people from seven Muslim-majority countries. Curbelo said at the time: \"I expect that these executive orders are in fact temporary and that once the Administration strengthens the vetting process, we can continue our tradition of welcoming those who are persecuted, in an orderly manner and without any kind of religious test.\"<ref name=\"Timmons\">{{cite web\n  |title = The short (but growing) list of Republican lawmakers who are publicly condemning Trump\u2019s \"Muslim ban\"\n  |last = Timmons\n  |first = Heather\n  |website = [[Quartz (publication)|Quartz]]\n  |date = January 30, 2017\n  |accessdate = December 6, 2017\n  |url = https://qz.com/897532/the-very-short-list-of-republican-congressmen-who-are-publicly-condemning-president-trumps-muslim-ban/\n  |ref = harv\n}}</ref> He said the executive orders \"were hastily issued & need a lot of work.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Man|first1=Anthony|title=South Florida political, religious leaders condemn Trump's travel ban|url=http://www.sun-sentinel.com/news/politics/fl-south-florida-democrats-trump-policies-20170130-story.html|accessdate=January 23, 2018|publisher=Sun Sentinel|date=January 30, 2017}}</ref>\n\nAs of September 2018, [[FiveThirtyEight]] found that Curbelo had voted in line with President Trump 82% of the time, and was the sixth-most partisan Trump supporter in the House when compared to his district's voting patterns.<ref name=\"Five38\">[https://projects.fivethirtyeight.com/congress-trump-score/house/ Tracking Congress in the Age of Trump], accessed September 25, 2018</ref>\n\n===Guns===\nThe Brady Campaign, a gun control advocacy group, labeled Curbelo an \u201cNRA lap dog\u201d for his support of the 2nd Amendment.<ref name=\"mcclatchydc.com\">Rosen, James; Carlos Curbelo isn\u2019t your typical Republican congressman from Miami; McClatchy; October 7, 2016; [https://www.mcclatchydc.com/news/politics-government/election/article106709612.html]</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Curbelo introduced a bill to ban [[bump stock]]s in the wake of the [[2017 Las Vegas shooting]].<ref name=\"Cadei122117\">{{cite web|last1=Cadei|first1=Emily|title=With tax vote, California Republicans take a 2018 gamble|url=http://www.modbee.com/news/article191146244.html|website=Modesto Bee|accessdate=December 24, 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\nAppearing on ABC's \u201cThis Week\u201d on February 18, 2018, Curbelo called on Republican congressional leaders to introduce gun-control measures.<ref>Lim, Naomi; Carlos Curbelo: Republican leaders need to bring gun legislation to the floor of Congress for debate; Washington Examinder; February 18, 2018; [https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/carlos-curbelo-republican-leaders-need-to-bring-gun-legislation-to-the-floor-of-congress-for-debate]</ref>\n\n===Tax reform===\nCurbelo voted in favor of the [[Tax Cuts and Jobs Act of 2017]].<ref name=\"Almukhtar\">{{cite web|last1=Almukhtar|first1=Sarah|title=How Each House Member Voted on the Tax Bill|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2017/12/19/us/politics/tax-bill-house-live-vote.html?_r=0|website=The New York Times|accessdate=December 24, 2017|date=December 19, 2017}}</ref> The ''[[Miami New Times]]'' projected that Curbelo's wife, who owns a [[Flow-through entity|pass-through]] [[Limited liability company|LLC]], would financially benefit from the TCJA's pass-through deduction enabling such companies to deduct a portion of their profits on taxes. He says the bill will \"make American families more prosperous.\"<ref name=\"Iannelli122217\">{{cite web|last1=Iannelli|first1=Jerry|title=Miami Rep. Curbelo's Wife Owns Assets That Benefit From GOP Tax Bill's Last-Minute Provision|url=http://www.miaminewtimes.com/news/rep-carlos-curbelo-benefits-from-gop-tax-bill-9930983|website=Miami New Times|accessdate=December 24, 2017|date=December 22, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Cannabis===\n\nCurbelo has a \"B\" rating from [[NORML]] for his voting history regarding [[cannabis]]-related causes. Curbelo supports veterans having access to medical marijuana if recommended by their [[Veterans Health Administration]] doctor and if it is legal for medicinal purposes in their state of residence.<ref name=\"NORML\">{{cite web|title=Florida Scorecard|url=http://norml.org/congressional-scorecard/florida|website=NORML|accessdate=December 24, 2017|language=en-us}}</ref>\n\n===LGBT rights===\n\nCurbelo supports [[same-sex marriage]]. Upon the landmark Supreme Court ruling ''[[Obergefell v. Hodges]]'', Curbelo stated \"I applaud the Supreme Court's ruling, and send my sincerest congratulations to all those who will finally enjoy the same legal rights as their peers.\"<ref name=\"Derby62715\">{{cite web|last1=Derby|first1=Kevin|title=Same-Sex Marriage Not Much of a Dividing Line in South Florida Congressional Race|url=http://sunshinestatenews.com/story/same-sex-marriage-not-much-dividing-line-south-florida-congressional-race|website=Sunshine State News|accessdate=December 24, 2017|language=en|date=June 27, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Immigration===\nCurbelo is \"an outspoken proponent of immigration reform.\"<ref name=hill>{{cite news|last1=Bernal|first1=Rafael|title=Curbelo won't support any spending bill unless 'DACA issue is resolved'|url=http://thehill.com/latino/362161-curbelo-wont-support-any-spending-bill-unless-daca-issue-is-resolved|accessdate=January 23, 2018|publisher=The Hill|date=November 28, 2017}}</ref> On July 23, 2015, he voted against legislation penalizing sanctuary cities.<ref name=\"mcclatchydc.com\"/> In November 2017, he said he would oppose any appropriations bill to fund the government past December 31 unless Congress passed permanent protections for recipients of [[Deferred Action for Childhood Arrivals]] (DACA), which currently impacts nearly 700,000 people and which President Trump rescinded in September 2017.<ref name=hill/> Curbelo has pushed for a permanent version of DACA and is a co-sponsor of a bill on the topic developed with the bipartisan [[Problem Solvers Caucus]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kopan|first1=Tal|title=Republican won't vote for government funding without DACA deal|url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/11/28/politics/daca-deal-government-funding-carlos-curbelo/index.html|accessdate=January 23, 2018|publisher=CNN|date=November 28, 2017}}</ref> In December 2017, Curbelo, who was leading talks with Democrats on immigration overhaul, criticized leaders of the Problem Solvers Caucus for withholding details of a potential bipartisan compromise on immigration policy. He introduced \"a slightly more conservative version of the [[DREAM Act]]\" but said that he would vote for the DREAM Act or more liberal proposals if they ever came up for a vote.<ref>{{cite news|last1=O'Keefe|first1=Ed|title=Key GOP voice on immigration accuses bipartisan caucus of withholding a potential \u2018dreamers\u2019 compromise|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/powerpost/wp/2017/12/11/key-gop-voice-on-immigration-accuses-bipartisan-caucus-of-withholding-a-potential-dreamers-compromise/|accessdate=January 23, 2018|publisher=Washington Post|date=December 11, 2017}}</ref> He filed the Recognizing America's Children Act (RAC) and said he would \"support any bill that has a chance of putting DACA protections into law.\"<ref name=hill/> In April 2018, he became a co-sponsor of the DREAM Act.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Daugherty|first1=Alex|title=Carlos Curbelo signs on to the DREAM Act|url=http://www.miamiherald.com/news/politics-government/article209986149.html|accessdate=May 7, 2018|publisher=Miami Herald|date=April 27, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn July 6, 2018, Curbelo was denied entry by the Department of Health and Human Services into a government facility housing immigrant minors separated from their parents at the Mexican border. He had made arrangements with HHS two weeks earlier for the visit, but the night before the planned visit was told he would not be permitted to enter the facility.<ref>Desidario, Andrew; Florida Republican Rep. Carlos Curbelo Blasts HHS for Barring Him From Visiting Detained Kids; Daily Beast; July 6, 2018; [https://www.thedailybeast.com/florida-republican-rep-carlos-curbelo-blasts-hhs-for-barring-him-from-visiting-detained-kids]</ref>\n\n===Abortion===\nCurbelo voted against defunding [[Planned Parenthood]]. He also voted against repealing a District of Columbia law that protects employees from employer retaliation when they have abortions, use birth control, or make other reproductive choices.<ref name=\"mcclatchydc.com\"/>\n\n===Keystone pipeline===\nCurbelo voted for the Keystone pipeline.<ref name=\"mcclatchydc.com\"/>\n\n===Charter schools===\nHe has voted increase private school vouchers.<ref name=\"mcclatchydc.com\"/>\n\n===Iran deal===\nCurbelo voted against the Iran nuclear deal.<ref name=\"mcclatchydc.com\"/>\n\n==Personal life==\nCurbelo married Cecilia Lowell, sister of former [[Miami Marlins|Marlins]] third baseman [[Mike Lowell]], in 2006 and resides in [[Kendall, Florida]].<ref name=\"votesmart\" />\n\nHe was diagnosed with [[Pertussis|whooping cough]] in August 2015. He was vaccinated as a child but did not receive the recommended booster shots as an adult. At the time of his diagnosis he said: \"I want to use this opportunity to remind parents to vaccinate their children against this dangerous infection. Adults should be aware that booster shots are necessary in order to maintain the vaccine's effectiveness.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://miami.cbslocal.com/2015/08/04/freshman-gop-rep-curbelo-diagnosed-with-whooping-cough/|title=Freshman GOP Rep. Curbelo Diagnosed With Whooping Cough|access-date=February 26, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Hispanic Americans in the United States Congress]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em|refs=\n<ref name=\"votesmart\">{{cite web|url=http://votesmart.org/candidate/biography/137676/carlos-curbelo#.VFk72_TF_Zk|title=Project Vote Smart - The Voter's Self Defense System|work=Project Vote Smart|accessdate=November 5, 2014}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat|Carlos Curbelo}}\n* [https://curbelo.house.gov Congressman Carlos Curbelo] official U.S. House website\n* [https://carloscurbelo.com/ Campaign website]\n* {{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/Florida/Government/Federal/US_House/Carlos_Curbelo_%5BR-26%5D}}\n* {{CongLinks | congbio = C001107 | votesmart=137676 | fec = H4FL26038 | congress = carlos-curbelo/C001107 }}\n* {{C-SPAN|carloscurbelo}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Joe Garcia|Joe Garc\u00eda]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[List of United States Representatives from Florida|U.S. House of Representatives]]<br>from [[Florida's 26th congressional district]]|years=2015\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-prec|usa}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Ryan Costello]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Seniority in the United States House of Representatives|United States Representatives by seniority]]|years=325th}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Mark DeSaulnier]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{FL-FedRep}}\n{{U.S. Florida Representatives}}\n{{USHouseCurrent}}\n{{M-DCPS}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Curbelo, Carlos}}\n[[Category:1980 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:American politicians of Cuban descent]]\n[[Category:American Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:Cuban-American Republicans]]\n[[Category:Florida Republicans]]\n[[Category:Hispanic and Latino American members of the United States Congress]]\n[[Category:Living peo